fields.title: MISSION AND VISION STATEMENT
fields.description: This section explains the why the business exists. It expounds on the company's values and what does it aim to accomplish in the long run.  The mission and vision statement should be concise and clear lines. It should be the ethos of the organisation and ingrained in the organisation.

fields.title: Executive summary
fields.description: The executive summary of a business is a brief introduction of the entire business plan. It provides a short, concise, and optimistic overview of business that captures the reader's attention. The executive summary is usually the first thing a reader will read and if it's poorly written, it will also be the last thing. The executive summary should be relatively short and succinct.

fields.title: COMPANY DESCRIPTION
fields.description: A company description provides a basic and useful introduction. It provides the key deyails about a company. It gives out vital information such as where company is located, how large the company is, what is the business of the company and what company wishes to accomplish. It should give a brief intro about what products and services does the company offer.

fields.title: KEY SUCCESS FACTORS
fields.description: Key success factors are key indicators and milestones that company sets to measure the success of the company. It assists the management in assessing their performance based on strentghs of business or its management team or personnel.

fields.title: OBJECTIVES
fields.description:
Objectives highlights the long term goals of the company in the form of financial, strategic and operational segment. Objectives should be SMART and realistic.
The SMART (Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Realistic, and Timed) structure is useful for testing assumptions and ensuring that it can really be implemented.

fields.title: INDUSTRY ANALYSIS
fields.description: In this section, you will provide the data and statistics regarding the industry and markets in which the company plans to enter.  Analysing the information will enable you to identify the risks and opportunities confronting the company and develop strategies to take the full benefit of opportunities and devising the ways to minimise the impact of adverse situations.

fields.title: TAM-SAM-SOM Analysis
fields.description: The analysis provides an idea about the size of the industry which is targeted by the company. Investors are always looking for the profitable ventures so that their investments gets multiplied. This analysis will help the potential investors to take the decisions with regard to pooling their money into the venture or not.

fields.title: SWOT ANALYSIS
fields.description: SWOT analysis is the summary of strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats being faced by the company for operating in the targeted industry. The company can perform a SWOT analysis as a way of deciding which marketing strategy to implement.

fields.title: INSIGHTS
fields.description: Insight provides an idea to the potential investors about the growth opportunities which will be captured by the company and how the company will take effective decisions leading to the success of the business in future.

fields.title: Marketing Plan
fields.description: The marketing plan section of the business plan explains how company is going to get their customers to buy its products and/or services. The plan should explain the characteristics of your market and suggest how much of the market company is expecting  to capture. A strong Market plan also shows why customers want to buy what you offer rather that the competition’s products or services.

fields.title: Ownership and Management Plan
fields.description: The Management and Ownership section of a business plan features short (one to three paragraphs) biographies of the key personnel involved in forming and running the business. It covers the sections like management summary, personnel hiring plan, corporate structure and job descriptions etc.

fields.title: MILESTONES
fields.description: Milestones breakdown a plan into quantifiable dates with specific deadlines, and management responsibilities. Milestones lists all key actions and goals for products, services, marketing, administration, and finance. It includes launch dates, review dates, prototype availabilities, advertising, social media, website development, and programs to generate leads and traffic. It also includes goals in terms of reaching X sales by Y date etc.

fields.title: 1. Mission
fields.instruction: Outline the main purpose of company's business.

fields.title: 2. Vision
fields.instruction: The company's vision statement should highlight how business's future will look like if the mission is achieved.

fields.title: 1. About the Industry
fields.instruction:
New Business: Highlight the brief introduction of the industry in which the company wishes to operate and how it will be beneficial to the company to work under particular circumstances in the industry.
Existing business: Provide the details regarding the industry in which the company wishes to expand and how the prevailing market conditions will help the company to grow in future thereby increasing their market reach.

fields.title: 2. About the Company
fields.instruction:
In the case of Existing business, provide the details regarding business name, location, company number and expansion plan of the company. Also, mention the number of employees and the foundation date of the company.
In the case of New business, provide the details with respect to business name, location, employees and expected date of launch

fields.title: 3. Problem
fields.instruction: The problem statement will highlight the challenges faced by customers which are not currently solved by the businesses that are operating in the targeted region.

fields.title: 4. Solution
fields.instruction: This section will highlight the solutions which are to be incorporated in the business model of the company in order to solve the issues faced by the targeted customers.

fields.title: 5. Business Model
fields.instruction: The section will provide the details regarding the products or services to be offered by the company along with their prices.

fields.title: 6. External Environment and competition
fields.instruction: Provide the details regarding the closest competitors of the company or organisation, including unique products or services offered by the company which is not at present offered by the competitors. Also, provide the strong points of the competitors which will help the company to improve its working and offerings.

fields.title: 7. Summary of financial analysis
fields.instruction: Pull data with graphs and Pie charts from Financial modelling Excel sheet.

fields.title: 8. Management team
fields.instruction: This section will provide information related to who are the key management personnel of the company and how their experience will help in guiding the employees and formulating strategies for the success of the business.

fields.title: 1. Company Name
fields.instruction: Provide the official name of the business.

fields.title: 2. Type of Business Structure
fields.instruction: Mention the type of business structure in which the business is established -Sole proprietorship, LLC, partnership, company or corporation?

fields.title: 3. Location
fields.instruction: This section will highlight the location where the company is incorporated or to be incorporated.

fields.title: 4. Company History
fields.instruction:
Existing Business
Provide information related to, when was the business started, what inspired it to start the business and what need does the company fulfill?
New Business
Provide details regarding, from where did the founders get the idea of formation of company or organisation and what were the factors that contributed to that decision.

fields.title: 5. Products/Services and Target Market
fields.instruction: A brief overview of what company plans to sell and to whom.

fields.title: Key Success Factors
fields.instruction:
List Key success factors based on following factors:
  1. Strategic Focus (Leadership, Management, Planning, location advantage ,Unique products)
  2. People (Personnel, Staff, Learning, Development)
  3. Operations (Processes, Work, technology)
  4. Marketing (Customer Relations, Sales, Responsiveness, competitive Pricing)
  5. Finances (Assets, Facilities, Equipment)

fields.title: 1. Strategic
fields.instruction: It includes long-term actions which are important for achieving the goals of the company. It is focused on creating long-term competitive advantage and strong positioning of the company in its target market.

fields.title: 2. Operational
fields.instruction: It includes measurable short-term goals that assist a company in obtaining its strategic or long-term goals. Operational objectives are usually evaluated using performance measures that help a company determine whether it is on track or not.

fields.title: 3. Financial
fields.instruction: This section focuses on achieving acceptable profitability in a company’s pursuit of its mission/vision, long-term health, and ultimate survival. It outlines the key financial highlights of the financial projections in the form of EBITDA, net worth, revenue and net profit margins etc.

fields.title: 1. Brief Overview of the Industry
fields.instruction: This section will define the industry that your company belongs to, components of the industry and statistics regarding the market size, growth rates and reasons to invest in that industry.

fields.title: 2. Industry Statistics
fields.instruction: This section will include specific data sets with respect to the location of business including market size of the industry in the country of incorporation, key statistics of the industry, employment generated through the industry, spending by the targeted customers on the products, services to be provided etc.

fields.title: 3. Trends and Growth Patterns
fields.instruction: An analytical review of trends and growth patterns will be studied based on performance of existing companies in the relevant industry. Growth of every business depends upon the preferences of customers whom it is targeting. A study about the spending habits, growth in demand for the product or service, future growth rates expected in the industry, pricing patterns for the product or service etc. will help you to better frame the strategies for the business.

fields.title: 4. Describe your business and how it fits into the industry
fields.instruction:
This section will include predicting the future of the company based on data collected through detailed market research including short term and long term expectations.
The section will also provide how the trends in the relevant industry would impact the business of the company.

fields.title: 5. Target Market
fields.instruction:
This section includes:
  • Who are the targeted customers of the company?
  • Demographics of the targeted population?
  • Statistics regarding the size of the target market?
  • Strategies to capture the targeted customers?

fields.title: 6. Competitors Analysis
fields.instruction:
This section includes both current competition and potential competitors who might enter the market. Answer the following questions before analysing your competitors :
  - What are their strengths?
  - What are their weaknesses?
  - What are their basic objectives?
  - What marketing strategies do they use?
  - What markets or market segments your competitors serve?
  - What benefits your competitors offers?

fields.title: 7. Location Analysis
fields.instruction: Location Analysis helps determine the market demand (especially for certain kind of industries), the positioning of the product and service and why a particular location has been chosen to house the business. The section takes into account demographics, census ,number of target customers and competitors.

fields.title: 1. TAM
fields.instruction: This section includes the total possible demand for the business. It includes the total number of customers who could use your product. TAM enables to assess the upside potential.

fields.title: 2. SAM
fields.instruction: It includes the portion of TAM that is currently targeted by the company. It also takes into account the competition faced by the company.

fields.title: 3. SOM
fields.instruction: SOM is based on the market the company can realistically serve. This section highlights the most realistic expectation of the current potential of the company's product or service.

fields.title: 1. Strengths
fields.instruction:
It is very important for any business to answer all these questions to understand what all are the strengths that can lead to the success of the company:
  - What is unique about the company's business?
  - What do company offer that is better than anyone else in the area?
  - What are company's areas of particular expertise?
  - What makes it better than its competitors?
  - What are the things that other people say the company does well?

fields.title: 2. Weaknesses
fields.instruction:
Answer all these questions before understanding the weaknesses of the organisation:
  - What’s the main area company need to improve on immediately?
  - What areas do its competitors have an advantage on?
  - Areas of lack of knowledge?
  - What are the things company is not so confident about?
  - Do company has enough investment to start such a project?
  - What resources do it lack?

fields.title: 3. Opportunities
fields.instruction:
Business opportunities highlights the areas of greatest potential in growing the business. These opportunities could include opening up a new market, new product initiatives or a new approach to an existing market. It is vital to have answers of all these questions to grab the opportunities at the right time.
  - What external changes will bring opportunities?
  - What is the competition ignoring that company can play in its favour?
  - What is missing in the market?
  - Can the company provide that missing link for the consumers?

fields.title: 4. Threats
fields.instruction:
A threat is an external factor (outside the business) that may affect the performance of the business. The most obvious effect would be a reduction in corporate sales. So it is very important for a businessman to analyze all these threats on time so that it will not lead to the failure of the company.
  - What are the main challenges that will be faced by the company?
  -What are the things that are holding the company back?
  - What are the negative aspects of the current market?
  - What are the obstacles the company is facing in the current scenario?
  - Are the government regulations going to affect the company?
  - Will political instability hurt the company?

fields.title: Insights
fields.instruction:
Provide Key Insights on the Target market mainly:
  - How big the target market is?
  - Identify potential customer.
  - Key statistics which shows the demand of the product in the market.
  - Short and long-term objectives of the Company.

fields.title: 1. Product
fields.instruction:
This section describes that the company should focus on the uniqueness of the product or services, that will set it apart from the competitors. The company should focus on answering all these questions:
  - Describe the company's product or service?
  - How it benefits the customer?
  - What sets it apart from competitor's offerings (i.e. what is company's USP)?
  -Mention specific benefits which will entice target customers?

fields.title: 2. Price
fields.instruction:
This section involves determining the price of the product or service. The price has to be both competitive and should allow the company to make a sustainable profit. The following questions should be answered before setting the price:
  - Describe how the company intends to price product or service?
  - What is the cost of company's product or service?
  - What is the company's competitor's pricing?
  - What kind of ROI the company is expecting and within what time frame?

fields.title: 3. Place
fields.instruction:
This section includes answers to the following questions:
  - Describe how the company will distribute products to the customer?
  - Which sales channels will be used?
  - Will the company be selling wholesale or retail?
  - Which channel will let the company economically reach its target audience?

fields.title: 4. Promotion
fields.instruction:
Promotion section of the marketing plan describes how the company is going to deliver its Unique Selling Proposition to the prospective customers. First, decide on the message that the company wants to convey to a targeted audience and then look at the promotion possibilities available to the company :
  - List the different media you will use to get your message to customers?
  - Will the company use sales promotional methods such as free samples, product demonstrations, etc.?
  - Calculate an approximate budget for advertising and promotion?
  -List Marketing or campaign Strategies
  - Approx. Leads expected out of strategies?

fields.title: 1. Management Summary
fields.instruction:
Under Management Summary provide a summary of your management team, including composition and years of experience (i.e. Our management team has over 20 years in the IT industry.)
Breakdown of the management team in general terms (i.e. We have a CEO and two managers reporting to him. The Project Manager will oversee the work of three virtual assistants.)

fields.title: 2. Personnel Hiring Plan
fields.instruction: This section generally highlights all the details relating to number of employees needed over a 3-5 year period, the titles of each staff member and forecasted salary, wage, and commission for each position.

fields.title: 3. Management Team and Corporate Structure

XYZ Partnership for Maternal, Newborn and Child Health
Strategic Objective 1: Prioritise engagement in Countries
XYZ organisation's country level efforts in order to align all stakeholders and the most affected communities in on-going inclusive dialogue and planning to shape priorities, policy, financing and programme decision-making in countries and places with the highest burden and need. The Partnership will have capacity to prioritise work in four to eight countries at a time, including countries that are the focus of the Global Financing Facility (GFF), providing support with advocacy, exchanges of innovative best practices, and engagement in accountability for the Global Strategy.
Strategic Objective 2: Drive accountability
Support and foster unified, independent and mutual accountability processes and platforms to hold all Partners to account for results, resources and rights. This should build accountability by duty bearers to rights holders, with advocacy to drive action for impact at sub-national, country, regional and global levels. This also includes support to the IAP for the development and dissemination of their annual report.
Strategic Objective 3: Focus action for results
Galvanize policy, programme and budget support to achieve strong health and well-being outcomes for women, new-borns, children and adolescents, especially in relation to the four core targets prioritized by the Partnership. Increased attention and evidence-based action on reducing inequity and addressing “frontier” issues - such as stillbirths, sexual and reproductive health and rights (SRHR) and adolescent health, and including focus on humanitarian and conflict-affected settings. Promote greater Partner participation in inter-sectoral knowledge sharing, action and accountability to deliver health results for women, children and adolescents.
Strategic Objective 4: Deepen Partnership
Facilitate and support collective action to drive effective policies, programmes, finance and accountability, relying upon the strengthened balanced and inclusive engagement of diverse and committed Partners in joint platforms, processes, and governance structures. This deepening of the Partnership is a foundation of the PMNCH offer, enabling Partners to achieve more collectively than they can as individual organisations.

fields.title: NPO- Helping in Children's Growth
fields.example: Between 2007 and 2012, the number of children living in poverty increased by over 20% to 16 million. Black and Hispanic children are more than twice as likely to live in poverty as those who are White, non‐Hispanic. Children growing up in areas of concentrated poverty face the absence of critical resources needed for healthy development. Extreme obstacles, such as generational school failure; parental substance use and incarceration; violence in the home and surrounding community; and teen pregnancy create a cycle where children fail within education, behavioural health and foster care systems, and too frequently land in the justice system. These entrenched generational challenges cause day‐to‐day barriers impeding children’s success in school and their success participating in traditional youth programs and services.

ACCOUNTANCY PROFESSION – MARKET SIZE
The accountancy profession supported a GDP contribution of £52 billion in 2016. This was made up of £17.2 billion generated by the accounting industry itself, alongside an estimated £34.5 billion contributed by the work of in-house accountants across other sectors of the economy. This figure amounts to a substantial portion of the UK economy, equivalent to 3 percent of all activity.
ACCOUNTANCY PROFESSION – INCREASED EMPLOYMENT
In total, 599,000 people were employed in accounting roles in the UK during 2016. This figure includes around 447,200 in-house accountants and 151,400 within specialist accounting services firms. The accounting industry itself also employs a further 242,800 support staff in non-accountancy roles. In other words, the accountancy profession directly supported the employment of 841,000 people.
